<DOC><DOCNO> AP900108-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-90 1230EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-AuntBee     01-08 0246</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Aunt Bee,0255</SECOND><HEAD>Aunt Bee Leaves Estate To Pinehurst Hospital, Public TV</HEAD><DATELINE>SILER CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The woman who portrayed the kindly AuntBee on television's ``The Andy Griffith Show'' left her house tothe town hospital and its contents to a center for publictelevision, an attorney said.   ``Anybody who reads the will can see that she remembered thosewho remembered her at the last moments,'' attorney Sam Williamssaid about how Frances Bavier divided her $700,000 estate.   The huge brick-and-stone house where Ms. Bavier died in hersleep was bequeathed to Moore Memorial Hospital in Pinehurst, wherethe actress was treated several times.   Ms. Bavier was admitted to two or three times to the hospital,most recently around last August for an undisclosed ailment,Williams said.   The contents of the house, where Ms. Bavier died at 86 on Dec.6, were donated to the University of North Carolina Center forPublic Television, he said.   The garage contains her green 1966 Studebaker, which hasn't beendriven since 1983.   Ms. Bavier shared her home with 15 cats. Her friends placed allthe animals in private homes, except for a black one that has beentoo quick to catch.   Ms. Bavier has lived in the southern North Carolina home since1972.   It showcased her belongings, including her cherished Emmy Award,her collection of leather-bound books and photograph albums. Thepictures include photographs of a young Ron Howard from his days asAunt Bee's charge, Opie.</TEXT></DOC>